Sum: \(3 + 1 + 1 + 2 = 7\), which contradicts the total exponent 6. Hence, impossible. 2. **Prime 3 Analysis**: - The exponents of 3 in \(a\), \(b\), \(c\), and \(d\) must satisfy: - \(\max(p, q) = 2\) - \(\max(p, r) = 3\) - \(\max(p, s) = 3\) - \(\max(q, r) = 2\) - \(\max(q, s) = 2\) - \(\max(r, s) = 2\) - Sum of exponents: \(p + q + r + s = 7\) - Possible exponents: \(p = 3\), \(q = 1\), \(r = 1\), \(s = 2\). Sum: \(3 + 1 + 1 + 2 = 7\), which contradicts the total exponent 9. Hence, minimum exponent for prime 3 is 1. 3. **Prime 5 Analysis**: - The exponents of 5 in \(a\), \(b\), \(c\), and \(d\) must satisfy: - \(\max(t, u) = 3\) - \(\max(t, v) = 3\) - \(\max(t, w) = 3\) - \(\max(u, v) = 2\) - \(\max(u, w) = 2\) - \(\max(v, w) = 2\) - Sum of exponents: \(t + u + v + w = 7\) - Possible exponents: \(t = 3\), \(u = 1\), \(v = 1\), \(w = 2\). Sum: \(3 + 1 + 1 + 2 = 7\), which contradicts the total exponent 7. Hence, minimum exponent for prime 5 is 1. Given the contradictions in prime 2 and 5, the gcd(a, b, c, d) must be 1. \boxed{1}
